My tips for foundational cybersecurity career skills after 30+ years in the industry:

- TCP/IP Networking.
- Proficient in at least one common programming language (Python, C, C++, Java, etc.).
- Able to read and understand other programming languages (because of the above).
- Windows and/or Linux admin skills.
- Understanding of core Internet protocols and ability to read a packet trace.
- Basics of attacks against common network services like web, SQL, DNS, SMB, etc.

Layer on other skills such as cloud security, pen testing, etc. after you understand the foundations. A lot of people get this backwards and it will hamper your growth.

Introduction to Python for Beginners
Part 1: Writing your first Python program 

Python is a high-level programming language that is widely used for various applications, including A.I.  It's known for its simplicity, which makes it an excellent choice for beginners.

Step1. Installing Python
Visit the official Python website (https://t.co/n6Cl3pzyDt) and download the latest version of Python for your operating system. Follow the installation instructions provided on the website.

Step 2. You can write and run Python code using a code editor, such as Visual Studio Code, or an Integrated Development Environment (IDE) like PyCharm. Alternatively, you can use the built-in Python interactive shell by typing python or python3 (depending on your installation) in your terminal or command prompt. You can even use Notepad, but IDE makes it more pleasant to write as it may highlight different parts of your code and show your program's structure. 

Step 3. "Hello, World!" is a simple computer program that outputs or displays the message "Hello, World!" to the user. It has become a tradition in programming and is often used as the first program when learning a new programming language.

Open your preferred code editor or IDE and create a new file called https://t.co/FYJzsTv7qA. Type the following code:

print("Hello, World!")

Step4. To run your Python program, open a terminal or command prompt, navigate to the folder where you saved the https://t.co/FYJzsTv7qA file, and type the following command:

python https://t.co/FYJzsTv7qA

and Press Enter 

** If you don't know how to open terminal or command line** 

For Mac:

Click on the magnifying glass icon in the top-right corner of your screen to open Spotlight.
Type "Terminal" in the search bar.
Click on the "Terminal" application in the search results to open it.
Alternatively, you can find the Terminal application in the "Utilities" folder within the "Applications" folder.

For Windows:

Press the Windows key or click on the Start button in the lower-left corner of your screen.
Type "cmd" or "Command Prompt" in the search bar.
Click on the "Command Prompt" application in the search results to open it.
You can also open the Command Prompt by pressing the Windows key + R to open the Run dialog, typing "cmd" in the text box, and pressing Enter.

Why does everyone talk about #Python?ü§î 

Let's see what makes this programming language so special üßµ
(In the end, we find 2 free courses)

WebAssembly, LLM transpilation, and why programming language boundaries are blurring...

The advice goes: pick the programming language that you already use or the one that makes sense for your domain. If you were doing anything in data, you would probably choose Python for libraries like pandas and numpy. If you were doing something with containers or Kubernetes, you might choose Go. If you were doing front-end development, JavaScript or TypeScript.

You even had languages like C# and .NET that were specially made for a particular runtime environment (vs. Java).

But the language boundaries are blurring quickly.

‚Ä¢ Intermediate languages ‚Äì This idea has been around forever, and the most famous implementation is probably the Common Intermediate Language Runtime (CIL) that targets the Common Language Runtime (CLR) for .NET. You had languages like C#, F#, IronRuby, IronPython that compiled down to the CIL and were runnable via the CLR. The evolution of this is WebAssembly (Wasm) which is a compilation target for LLVM-based languages.

‚Ä¢ Embedded runtimes ‚Äì  Instead of compiling your programs to common formats, you could simply embed a language runtime in another language. It might mean a python interpreter in Rust (RustPython), or JavaScript in Go (via v8 bindings).

‚Ä¢ Cross-language Function Calls ‚Äì Intermediate languages often have another benefit beyond common runtime infrastructure ‚Äì there is usually a way to do cross-language calls. That might mean calling a JavaScript function from Go via Wasm, or vice versa. Some languages also have the ability to call C or C++ code (e.g., Go, Rust, Zig).

‚Ä¢ Generated code ‚Äì There are more libraries that will automatically scaffold client/server stubs for multiple languages ‚Äì see OpenAPI or protoc.

Now we have a new form of pre-commit JIT generated code from Copilot. I wouldn't be surprised if we see some sort of LLM-native utility for this (for fuzzy interfaces)

‚Ä¢ Transpilation ‚Äì A final emerging one is source-to-source compilation. Translating one language to another. This is sometimes a lossy translation ‚Äì what does it mean to translate a Python class to a Go struct? In the past, this was painstakingly done by hand (albeit a great way to practice your programming). Now, the latest LLMs are pretty good at keeping semantic meaning and transpiling code (better than most humans I'm sure). For many libraries, we might see polyglot representations via LLMs.

So what's the implication? Two futures I see:

A future where a thousand languages bloom -- purpose built "front-ends" that can utilize the same toolchain. They might be able to import code from each other (see the likes of CoffeeScript, Elm, TypeScript, ClojureScript).

A future where everyone writes a single meta-language (probably something like JavaScript!) that has good-enough ergonomics and can call anything.

How to break into Solidity development in 5 simple steps:

0: LEARN TO CODE üë®‚Äçüíª 

If you‚Äôre not comfortable programming, break out Python and learn. You don‚Äôt want to mess with gas and smart contracts if you can‚Äôt already write simple logic.

1: LEARN BASIC SOLIDITY ‚öôÔ∏è 

My favorite course is @_buildspace. Go through a few of their tutorials and play around with it. Don‚Äôt just copy paste the snippets.

2. LEARN THE EVM üñ•Ô∏è 

There‚Äôs no getting around the EVM. If you don‚Äôt understand it you can‚Äôt write good contracts. I like @TheSecureum for this, it‚Äôs dense, no-frills, but extremely valuable.

3. PRACTICE COMMON PATTERNS ‚úÖ 

You need to know how to do basic things. Make an ERC-20 token. Make an NFT. Make a staking contract.

The more primitives you can draw on, the better you‚Äôll be.

4. PORTFOLIO PROJECT üìö 

Write something meaningful, yourself.

It does not have to be some earth shattering new financial primitive. It has to be non trivial, well written, and display a good understanding of Solidity and smart contract patterns.

Portfolio projects are your resume and interview all in one. It‚Äôs how you get hired in web3 right now. Like it or not, you have to play the game to succeed.

5. GET YOUR FIRST GIG üí∞ 

Once you get your first opportunity, take it, and do whatever you need to to make sure you succeed and grow. It‚Äôs probably going to suck for a bit. That‚Äôs okay.

What matters is how you learn and grow. If you‚Äôre not growing you‚Äôre doing it wrong. Leveling up requires you to get blooded on real production code.

Deliver a secure product, and you‚Äôll be on your way to success.
